// PARSE-INVALID — Session 1.6 / Phase 2.7 chained-comparison rule.
//
// Phase 2.7 introduces binary comparison expressions (`<`, `>`)
// for mizan bound expressions. The grammar is NON-ASSOCIATIVE:
// chained comparisons of the form `a < b < c` or `a > b > c` are
// a parse error. Python's transitive-comparison shape is
// deliberately rejected — Furqan does not silently produce
// `a < b AND b < c` from `a < b < c` because the silent expansion
// is exactly the kind of zahir/batin divergence the language is
// built to detect (the source surface looks like a comparison;
// the depth is two ANDed comparisons).
//
// Per Phase 2.7 §6.4: after parsing one BinaryComparisonExpr,
// encountering another comparison operator at the same level
// emits a parser-layer marad-shaped diagnostic. The user must
// parenthesise explicitly or restructure the expression.
//
// Expected: ParseError with diagnosis text naming the chained-
// comparison rejection rule.

bismillah ChainedComparison {
    authority: NAMING_MD
    serves: purpose_hierarchy.balance_for_living_systems
    scope: calibrate
    not_scope: nothing_excluded
}

mizan chained_demo {
    la_tatghaw:  0.0 < false_positive_rate < 0.05
    la_tukhsiru: detection_rate > 0.90
    bil_qist:    calibrate(corpus, paired_fixtures)
}
